	abstract = {″Petri nets″ are graphs models used to study the interconnection properties of concurrent and parallel systems. Petri nets and their related graph models have been used to model a wide variety of systems, such as: event-condition occurrence systems, digital computers, software systems, etc. , asynchronous control arrays, legal systems, formal language theory, and communication protocols. It appears that Petri nets can also be used in studying the interconnection properties of large-scale distributed processor systems, which have recently received much interest because of the decline in hardware costs brought about by the LSI single-chip microprocessor. It has been shown that a Petri net (with a slight modification) is as powerful as the Turing machine in representing the coordination of asynchronous processes. The purpose of this paper is to introduce this modeling device to those who work in circuits and systems.},
